cards.name: Name for Statement about Textual Work

cards.description:
In many cases, current data does not support the level of specificity that the full ontology allows, or the information is simply best expressed in human-readable form. For example, instead of a completely modeled set of parts with materials, many museum collection management systems allow only a single human-readable string for the "medium" or "materials statement".  Any time that there is a description of the resource, with or without qualification as to the type of description, then this branch can be used to record the descriptive text.
See: https://linked.art/model/base/#statements-about-a-resource

cards.name: Name for Statement about Timespan of Creation Event

cards.description:
Dimensions are a combination of a numeric value, a unit for the value, and a classification as to what sort of value it is. They can be measured on the entity by some means, such as counting or using an instrument. The data structure is commonly used for physical things (e.g. height and width), but is also applicable to textual works (e.g. number of words) or even people (e.g. height, weight). If there is a countable feature, then that can be expressed as a dimension using this data structure.
See: https://linked.art/api/1.0/shared/dimension/ and https://linked.art/model/object/physical/#dimensions

cards.description:
The resource that references this assignment was assigned to its parent resource by this activity. This is especially useful for distinguishing the context of when a piece of data was known or asserted, for example when a measurement took place or the organization that assigned an identifier.
For example, a dimension of an object was assigned by the activity that measured the object, carried out by the curator (or other), or the accession number of the object was assigned to it by the registrar.

# Specific:

This branch allows the classifications themselves to be classified in order to know what sort of type it is, without recognizing all of them individually. This is important when the set of first degree types is not easily enumerable, such as classifications for the type of object or work.  See: https://linked.art/model/base/#types-of-types

nodes.description:
# Specific:


# General:
In many cases, current data does not support the level of specificity that the full ontology allows, or the information is simply best expressed in human-readable form. For example, instead of a completely modeled set of parts with materials, many museum collection management systems allow only a single human-readable string for the "medium" or "materials statement".  Any time that there is a description of the resource, with or without qualification as to the type of description, then this branch can be used to record the descriptive text. See: https://linked.art/model/base/#statements-about-a-resource

nodes.description:
# Specific:


# General:
In many cases, current data does not support the level of specificity that the full ontology allows, or the information is simply best expressed in human-readable form. For example, instead of a completely modeled set of parts with materials, many museum collection management systems allow only a single human-readable string for the "medium" or "materials statement".  Any time that there is a description of the resource, with or without qualification as to the type of description, then this branch can be used to record the descriptive text. See: https://linked.art/model/base/#statements-about-a-resource

nodes.description:
# Specific:


# General:
The resource that references this assignment was assigned to its parent resource by this activity. This is especially useful for distinguishing the context of when a piece of data was known or asserted, for example when a measurement took place or the organization that assigned an identifier. For example, a dimension of an object was assigned by the activity that measured the object, carried out by the curator (or other), or the accession number of the object was assigned to it by the registrar.
